snippet.textDisplay:
Not to be mean but... you should've drained that ramen before you actually ate it😅. Mi goreng stands for fried noodles. And we have the same product here in Malaysia. And it's kinda written on the guide on how to make it.
I'm not saying you can't have it that way, it's just that I once accidentally turned it into a noodle soup as I forgot to drain it and I kinda think it tasted horrible. If you really want the original full and better experience, drain the water before adding the spice. Because all the packets in there are to be used to make the noodle sauce not soup.😅
(It's like a samyang korean spicy noodles)

snippet.textDisplay: Hey, don't slander the roller food!  I have talked to the guys at my local 7-11.  They can't leave things on the rollers for longer than 4-5 hours and they have to heat up to at least 115 degrees before they can actually serve them; anything they fix in the oven has to be removed and discarded (though the employees can eat them if they want to) after four to five hours as well.  They usually sell through the roller things within three hours and have to restock.  Anything that looks dried out or unappetizing, call them on it.  If they don't follow up on that, they get complaints, and inspectors will come by and most states will hit them hard with a food license violation.  Your family ran a restaurant; like everyone else you're familiar with how that works. Inspectors come by when THEY want to, and your place had better meet the standards. At least around here, 7-11 gets inspected fairly frequently.
